          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">How Caravan Finance Works</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Caravan finance works similarly to a car loan — you borrow a set amount, repay it over an agreed term with interest, and the caravan or motorhome typically serves as security for the loan. The main differences from car finance are that caravans are available in a much wider price range (from $5,000 for a basic used pop-top to $200,000+ for a new luxury motorhome), finance terms can extend up to 10 years for higher-value units, and depreciation patterns differ from cars — quality caravans from reputable Australian manufacturers tend to hold their value better than mass-market imports.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The Australian caravan industry has experienced significant growth, with the Caravan Industry Association of Australia reporting strong sales and registrations year after year. Popular caravan brands in Australia include Jayco, New Age, Coromal, Crusader, Avida, Roadstar, Kokoda, and Lotus — many of which are manufactured locally. Motorhome brands include Winnebago, Avida, Sunliner, and Horizon. Australian-made products generally attract better finance terms due to strong resale values and parts support.</p>
        </section>

