          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Buying Tips: New vs Used Caravans</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">New caravans come with manufacturer warranties, the latest features, and your choice of specification. However, they depreciate noticeably in the first 1–2 years. Finance rates for new caravans are lower, but the purchase price is higher. A new Jayco Journey, for example, starts at approximately $45,000 — while a 2–3 year old model in good condition might be $30,000–$35,000.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Used caravans offer better value per dollar and the depreciation curve has flattened. However, it is essential to inspect thoroughly before buying — especially checking for water damage, structural integrity, tyre condition, electrical systems, and appliance function. For private purchases, a pre-purchase inspection by a qualified caravan technician is highly recommended. Nik Finance can arrange finance for both dealer and private sale caravan purchases.</p>
